  "prompt": "Is money laundering a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a crime in virtually every country around the world. It is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. The goal is to make the money appear as if it comes from a legitimate source.\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it allows criminals to profit from their illegal activities without getting caught. It also undermines the integrity of financial institutions and can have serious economic and social consequences.\n\nLaws against money laundering are strict and typically include severe penalties, including substantial fines and imprisonment. In many jurisdictions, financial institutions are required to have robust systems in place to detect and report suspicious activities that might indicate money laundering.",
